It would be best if you created classes to represent your JSON, so you can deserialize it using `JsonConvert.DeserializeObject&lt;T&gt;(string json)`.
Then you can access your data using the properties.

If you only need the `SaveValues` and the value of `id` your classes can look like this:

    class DataObject
    {
         public PlayerHandler[] SaveValues { get; set; }
    }

The code to iterate all `ids` within all `SaveValues`(`PlayerHandler`) would look like this:

    var deserialized = JsonConvert.DeserializeObject&lt;DataObject[]&gt;(json);

    foreach (var dataObject in deserialized)
    {
          foreach (var playerHandler in dataObject.SaveValues)
          {
              var id = playerHandler.Id;
              //Do with Id whatever you want
              Debug.Log(id.ToString);
          }
    }

&lt;s&gt;If you need other values from `SaveValue` you can just add properties to the `SaveValue` class.&lt;/s&gt; *Obsolete due to Question changes.*

**Personally** I would almost always recommend to deserialize JSON into objects and then access the values instead of using JNode, JObject, etc. to improve the readability.

